heir faith in the new social and medical sciences, reformers pushed rehabilitation as a means to “rebuild” disabled soldiers, relieving the nation of a monetary burden and easing the decision to enter the Great War. Linker’s narrative moves from the professional development of orthopedic surgeons and physical therapists to the curative workshops, or hospital spaces where disabled soldiers learned how to repair automobiles as well as their own artificial limbs. The story culminates in the postwar establishment of the Veterans Administration, one of the greatest legacies to come out of the First World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDisabled veteransxRehabilitationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMedical rehabilitationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xVeteransxMedical carezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226482552423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226482552/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles